If someone were looking for a term that would define IBM’s strategy with great precision, the most approximate would be “long term”.
For the general public, IBM is the symbol of a technological revolution, a company that is perceived as current and yet it has been a hundred years since its foundation.
The basis for this long-term character was laid by the first head of the firm, visionary Thomas J. Watson Sr.
He already coined the motto that many problems in the world have a solution if people are willing to think.
His motto "Think!" became his seal, around which the life of the future giant will be built (it was also the title of an internal magazine that IBM began to publish in 1935).
Watson was also the basis of a carefully crafted corporate culture.
“For us, IBM implies long-term thinking, a continuous movement towards the future.
IBM has survived and thrived for a hundred years for that reason, because it remained true to its basic principles, but without fear of the changes around it.
This has enabled us, during our first century, to transform technology, business and society.
We look forward to thriving even more in our second century,” said Samuel J. Palmisano, the company’s current CEO.
A sophisticated system
Watson, as early as the 1930s, cared about caring for his employees as the Ba<0xC5><0xA5>a entrepreneur in the Czech Republic (IBM employees were among the first American workers to enjoy paid vacations, insurance, stylish uniforms and a sophisticated compensation system that rewarded the best inventors and sellers).
The same long-term sophistication is maintained by IBM in the customer relationship.
Already from the beginning the company knew how to discover talents (being one of the first companies in the world to end any type of discrimination, it could choose without problems).
In line with the anti-discrimination strategy is the current plan of IBM, by which Palmisano will be replaced next year by a woman: Virginia Rometty.
She has worked for 30 years at IBM, where she has been head of sales, marketing and strategy.
During the last years IBM has participated in the so-called virtual meetings, online brainstorming, from which arise endless future strategies and innovations.
Not surprisingly, there are plenty of ideas, as nearly half a million people work at the firm.
An institution with a good reputation
The fixed position in the business provides the company with a strong internal and external image.
“From the beginning, IBM maintained a concept of institution rather than technology company,” says Harvard Business School professor economist and author of the IBM book Rosabeth Moss Kanter.
“IBM is not a technology company, but a company that is trying to solve business problems for technology users,” said George Colony of Forrester Research.
As the company itself says there is a difference between entering the business and directly creating a business.
IBM - or the "Great Green" - as it is known in the U.S. familiarly because of its logo, has become in the last hundred years one of the largest companies in the world.
It is arguably the most versatile technology company (develops both equipment and programs, infrastructure and web hosting services within a wide range of services, ranging from servers to nanotechnology).
It holds the highest number of patents of all American technology companies and five of its employees have received the Nobel Prize.
Among his inventions are the ATM, payment cards, financial swaps, barcodes and floppy disks.
This year, IBM has become the second technology company by market capitalization (the first is Apple), when it first surpassed Microsoft in 1996.
Looking to the future
Not all products and innovations just satisfy the taste of customers and the moment (IBM did not bet on its own operating system, OS/2, Prodigy online services or IBM PCjr computers).
“If your business is based on advancing, it cannot be emotionally anchored in the past,” said Samuel J. Palmisano.
That’s why IBM has no problem building its bases on other platforms (and likewise, if they don’t work, it abandons them).
And this is the difference of the competition, Microsoft, which basically remains and always falls exclusively with Windows.
Technology of the future
In terms of sales, IBM is mainly dedicated to services, of which approximately one-fifth are programs and one-fifth are equipment.
However, even in 1990, equipment accounted for more than half of the suppliers' share.
As of 2000, IBM has sold low-yield assets for a total value of $15 billion. During the same period, it has invested $58 billion in the purchase of future technology.
Investments have continued since 2008, when the modern global financial crisis manifested itself for the first time.
IBM is acting on the premises of its first boss, Thomas J. Watson, who during the great economic crisis of 29 increased investments.
It seems that so far the IBM company has been able to cope with the crisis.
The value of IBM shares since the beginning of 2008 has grown stratospherically to 120%, the net profit of the company has not stopped increasing.
IBM’s motto is to change everything except its value.
It can therefore be expected that when the next crisis comes, this flexible giant will endure.
IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to Spaceflight
IBM (International Business Machines) was founded in New York a hundred years ago, its original name being Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was adopted as early as 1924 – originally a brand used in branches in Canada and South America.
The foundation for the birth of IBM stems from the merger of four companies dating back to the 1880s.
He possessed inventions such as the famous "ticketing clock", which allows controlling the entry and exit of employees.
The architect of the new company was businessman Charles Ranlett Flint, who until 1930 also chaired its supervisory board.
Flint hired the head of a competition company, Thomas J. Watson, to help him run the company.
The new leader overshadowed the IBM founder (Watson’s ideas remain the firm foundation on which corporate culture and identity are underpinned).
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as its name suggests, began with the production and sale of all kinds of business appliances, from meat and cheese cutters to cash registers.
During Watson’s first four years at the helm, revenue doubled by $9 million and the company’s massive expansion across continents began.
Watson was so crucial to the company that, after nearly forty years in the chair of the boss, he was replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s IBM staff and computers helped NASA guide flights to space (to Mercury, Saturn and in 1969 the famous flight to the Moon).
In 1964, IBM developed the first generation of computers, the IBM System/360 series.
The classic "fish", which established the standard of computers of that time, came to the market with the name of IBM 5150 in 1981.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, which, for its part, acquired the consulting part of the company Pricewaterhouse Coopers and began to offer a complete advice and services of high added value.
The strategy that IBM has paid for over the past three years is the Smarter Planet concept, that is, “a smarter planet.”
Its aim is to make more rational use of technology, although areas have not yet been planned and circumstances have not improved, for example, with regard to transport and city management.
For the retail sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smart Commerce” platform that allows retailers to manage the full business cycle.
IBM has a long history in this country.
In 1932 it opened a branch in Czechoslovakia, the first country to have it in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates the strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The headquarters for Central and Eastern Europe has is in Prague. Also here is a world-renowned research team working with voice recognition.
