7 Lessons from Steve Jobs’ Lost Interview Showed at a Theater This Week
After Steve Jobs’ death on October 5, there were some who compared him to Henry Ford – distinguishing the tech genius as the Great Modern Inventor.
But what Apple fans might find most revealing, in a recently rediscovered interview with Jobs that has been dusted off as a preview of a series of special screenings in major markets this week, is how much this creative mind understood about business processes and product workflows.
He was certainly a self-recognized designer, dreamer and hippie, but he was also a meticulous organizer and a junkie of flowcharts — a man who believed many executives suffered from “a disease that consists of thinking that a great idea is 90 percent of the work... [but] there’s a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringley was developing the television series The Triumph of the Nerds on the dawn of the personal computer, and sat for more than an hour with Jobs for an extensive and rare conversation.
At that time it had been barely 10 years since Jobs had been forced to leave Apple, and he was already working intensively on his new computer company NeXT, waiting for the popular adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringley’s interview was used on Nerds, he said the originals of the interview disappeared during transport.
It was only after Jobs’ death that a full VHS copy was discovered in the director’s garage.
This slightly re-released footage is the basis for Steve Jobs: The 68-minute Lost Interview, which hits Landmark theaters on Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly willing to expose his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And very thoughtful.
At four different points throughout the interview, there are great silences between questions and answers – from 10 to 15 seconds of reflections, where Jobs is clearly weighing his thoughts, looking for precision.
There are also times when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to the surface, where he seems impatient due to Cringley’s questions, pushing him to go faster towards the most important topics or arguments.
Filmed before the era of Pixar, the iPod or the iPhone, there’s something strangely prophetic about The Lost Interview, when Jobs evaluates what he sees other companies doing right and wrong, and offers his own vision of the future of computing.
It’s one thing to read posthumous reviews of Jobs’ career, but there’s something raw and inspiring about the Jobs we see here, the eager dreamer on the brink of greatness.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Not long after explaining everything in detail here, he went and did.
A quick summary of seven notable sequences from The Lost Interview:
About how you learned to run a business:
“Over the years in the business, I always asked, ‘Why do you do things?’ and the answers they give you invariably are, ‘Oh, that’s just the way it’s done.’
Nobody knows why he does what he does, in business nobody thinks about things very deeply.
That's what I found.
Jobs goes into detail on his efforts to simplify Apple’s accounting.
Bewildered by the way in which costs were recorded – often starting with a “standard cost” that was made to look good, and then adjusted with a “variable” – he developed an automated factory that ensured they could determine retail commercial costs.
The Pope's Joke:
Jobs narrates the “Blue Box” he built himself with Steve Wozniak – a device that allowed people to effectively hack the phone company and make long distance calls for free.
It has been widely written about the device, but Jobs’ euphoria here in describing the Blue Box as an act of empowerment is contagious.
He describes how he and Wozniak tested the box by using a pay phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another, while creating a loop with as many satellites as possible.
“We were wrapping things around the world a half dozen times and you were yelling through the payphone and I was coming back a minute later to the payphone next door,” Jobs says with a laugh.
“We were young and what we learned was that we could build something ourselves that could control billions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
The two of us, we didn’t know much, but we could build a small thing that could control a giant thing – it was an incredible lesson, and I don’t think Apple would ever have existed without it.
Jobs continues to describe a glorious joke that he and Wozniak almost abandoned, calling the Vatican through the Blue Box in the middle of the night and requesting to speak to the Pope while doing his best imitation of Henry Kissinger.
As several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the U.S. diplomat, the two burst into laughter just before the pope himself was awakened to go and answer the phone.
About falling in love with technology (and selling over the phone with Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, hunting for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked up Bill Hewlett in the phone book and made a call to him.
Shortly after his 20-minute phone conversation, Jobs got a part-time summer job at Hewlett-Packard.
“That was a remarkable influence on me, it was the only company I had seen at that age and shaped my vision of what a company was and how well they treated their employees.”
Jobs later became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
It was as big as a suitcase, it had a small cathode tube screen, and I fell in love with it.
I would get a trip to HP as a teenager and waste time with that machine and write programs for it.
Improving innovation:
At various points in the interview, Jobs talks about inventing new products on the go.
Early in his career, as he devoted himself to selling a handful of motherboards, he was asked by a customer if he could assemble the entire equipment.
Working with only 30 days of credit, I had to figure out the assembly and delivery of the finished devices.
Later, while at Apple, he recalled the struggles he faced in developing a computer mouse:
“I remember having dramatic arguments ... they were yelling at me that it would take five years [to create a mouse that would cost $300], and I got tired and went out and found a designer.
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could build for $15 and that was totally reliable.
About large companies losing strength:
Long before he led Apple’s renaissance, Jobs prophetically predicted how many industry leaders would stumble on his vision, and lose control of their market share.
“Tell me you work at IBM or Xerox, so you make better copiers and printers, so what?”
You have the monopoly of market share, so the company is no more successful.
Sales and marketing departments increase success, so it is these kinds of people who end up running companies and the people in charge of the products are kicked out of the forum for decision making.
The genius of the products that led to that position of monopoly rots because of people who do not have the notion of good products vs bad products - the knowledge of the necessary trade.
That's what happened at Xerox...
Xerox could have taken over the entire computer industry.
It could have been ten times its size, it could have been the Microsoft of the 90s...
They took the defeat of victory.
Innovation as an Artistic Expression:
“There’s a huge amount of work between a great idea and a great product... as the great idea evolves, changes and grows.”
A lot is learned about the subtleties of it.
There are sacrifices you have to do – some things you can’t do that electrons do, glass does, robots do, factories do.
You have to keep 5,000 things in your brain - these concepts - adjusting them all at once...
In the end it all comes down to taste – it goes down to trying to expose you to the best that a team of humans has done, and then trying to adapt those things to what you’re doing.
Picasso said that good artists copy, great artists steal.
We have never been embarrassed about stealing great ideas.
What partly made the Macintosh great was that the people who were working on it were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians, who casually were the best computer scientists in the world.
If it wasn’t for computers, you could be doing wonderful things in other fields.
Scalia and Thomas Dinner with Health Care Law Rivals as Court Accepts Case
The day the Supreme Court met behind closed doors to examine the politically controversial question of whether they would accept President Obama’s challenge to health care law, two of his magistrates, Antonin Scalia and Clarence Thomas, were gifted at a dinner sponsored by the law firm that will present the case to the high court.
The occasion came last Thursday, when the nine judges met in a preliminary hearing to thoroughly study the petitions for review.
One of the cases in question was a lawsuit filed by 26 states challenging total health care reform passed by Congress last year, a law that has been a war cry for conservative activists across the country.
The magistrates agreed to allow the lawsuit to proceed and, in fact, a five-and-a-half-hour historic plea is expected by March, and the outcome is likely to further cloud the 2012 presidential race, which will be in full swing by the time the court’s decision is known.
The lawyer who will appear in court and claim that the law should be scrapped will likely be Paul Clement, who served as U.S. Attorney General during the George W. Bush administration.
Clement’s law firm, Bancroft PLLC, was one of nearly two dozen companies that helped sponsor the annual dinner of the Federalist Society, a group that has been dedicated to advocating conservative legal principles for many years.
Another firm that sponsored the dinner, Jones Day, represents one of the trade associations that defied the law, the National Federation of Independent Businesses.
Another sponsor was pharmaceutical giant Pfizer Inc., which has a huge financial interest in the outcome of the litigation.
The dinner was held at a Washington hotel, hours after the court’s preliminary hearing on the case.
Attendees included Mitch McConnell, the top Republican in the Senate and a declared opponent of the health care law.
The special guests at dinner? Scalia and Thomas.
It’s nothing new: The two judges have been attending Federalist Society events for years.
And it is not something that conflicts with ethical norms.
In fact, judges are exempt from the Code of Conduct governing the actions of lower federal magistrates.
If they were not, it could be said that they would fall under Canon Code 4C, which says: “A judge may attend events to raise funds from law-related and other organizations, although the judge may not be a speaker, a guest of honor, or appear on the program of such an event.”
However, Scalia and Thomas’ absolute proximity to two of the law firms in the case, as well as a company with a huge financial interest, was enough to alarm ethics activists in the government.
“This impressive ethics gap and indifference to the code goes against the lawsuits of several magistrates that the court abides by the same rules that apply to all federal judges,” said Bob Edgar, president of Common Cause.
“The judges were gifted at a gala fundraiser with lawyers who have cases pending before the court.”
Their appearance and assistance in fundraising for this event undermines any demand for impartiality, and is unacceptable.
Scalia and Thomas have shown little interest in criticism that they say mix court activity too easily with the agenda pushed by groups like the Federalist Society.
And Thomas' wife, Ginni, is a prominent conservative activist.
On the other hand, conservatives argue that it is magistrate Elena Kagan, who has an ethical problem, not Scalia and Thomas.
Kagan worked as the Obama administration’s attorney general when the first legal challenges to the law were presented to the trial court.
Her critics have pushed for Kagan to refrain from seeing the case, saying she was too involved in defending the law to now be impartial.
Kagan has given no indication that he will.
Boeing receives record order of $18 billion
Emirates is ordering 50 twin-aisle Boeing 777s, with an option of 20 more.
Boeing also sells six Boeing Dreamliner aircraft to Oman Air, an operation valued at more than $1 billion.
It is rarely news when a company gets an order for 50 units of its product.
But it’s a big transaction when the company is the aircraft manufacturer Boeing Co. and the sale price for the 50 aircraft amounts to a record $18 billion.
It is as big as the place from which Boeing received the order: the Middle East, a growing gold mine of future aircraft orders.
In a study released Monday, the Chicago-based company estimates that over the next 20 years airlines in the Middle East will need 2,520 aircraft worth $450 billion.
Boeing announced over the weekend its largest order in history for commercial aircraft for their dollar value – 50 double-aisle Boing 777 jets.
The successful order came from the Emirates airline in Dubai.
The airline also has an option to buy 20 more aircraft, which would raise the total selling price to $26 billion, Boeing announced at the 2011 Dubai Airshow.
Then on Monday, Boeing said Oman Air had ordered six Boeing 787-8s, the so-called Dreamliner, which boasts fuel savings and spectacular passenger services.
The sale price for six of them is over a billion dollars.
“This clearly has a huge positive effect for Boeing,” Morningstar analyst Neal Dihora said.
"The quality of these particular customers is very strong."
Many Middle Eastern airlines are owned by their oil-producing nations.
Therefore, not only do they have the money to pay for the planes, but a rise in fuel prices – usually detrimental to airlines, because it is one of the biggest costs – is not so detrimental, because the country is making money with the rise in the price of oil.
That’s important because they are less likely than other airlines to cancel or delay flight orders when fuel prices rise, Dihora said.
“They have natural protection,” he said.
The Emirates order solidifies Boeing’s leadership in the widebody aircraft market and helps keep at bay its competitor Airbus SAS’ attempt to invade its dominance with the A350 passenger aircraft.
Boeing’s win at the air show comes four months after Airbus said it would delay the debut of the larger A350, which competes directly with the 777-300ER.
It delayed the debut to add more momentum after customers demanded an increase in payload and range.
Boeing Co shares rose 1.5% to $67.94.
Mexico's President's Sister Apparently Defeated in Michoacán Vote
Luisa María Calderón claims that the drug traffickers helped her PRI opponent, Fausto Vallejo, in the race for governor.
President Felipe Calderon's sister appears to have lost her candidacy for governor of Michoacán during the state's violent election, and she said Monday that drug traffickers helped tilt the race in favor of one of her opponents.
