“We have monumental challenges and we have to maintain a high level of growth.”
“It’s not an option, it’s an imperative, because where do we find employment for tens of millions of our young men and women.”
Others argue that developing economies like India have no responsibility to help rich Europeans when they face their own deep economic problems.
Ashutosh Varshney, a professor at Brown University in the U.S., said it would be politically very difficult to sell aid to Europe for India’s one billion two hundred thousand people, of whom up to 800 million live on about $2 a day or less.
“At some point they will realize that Greeks are retiring at the age of 50 and going on vacation to the beaches and that will not go well,” he said.
Lee Howell, managing director of the World Economic Forum, also wondered why India’s reserves should be used to keep the numerous and well-paid Greek public sector workers in jobs at poorly run, loss-generating companies like the railroads.
Mr Nag said the eurozone crisis threatens to have “significant chain effects” across Asia.
The Asian Development Bank’s forecast of 7.5 percent economic growth in Asia for 2011/12 now faces “downside risks” due to the threat from Europe.
He said vulnerable emerging markets needed to make “contingency plans” to protect themselves from a crisis and significant capital outflows from their economies.
Serious Pentagon Warnings About Possible Defense Cuts
Defense Secretary Leon Panetta warmed Congress on Monday, warning that automatic budget cuts looming could undermine national security and provoke a chain financial reaction from the Pentagon corridors, to Afghanistan’s battlefields, to civilian assembly lines.
The Pentagon is already digesting $450 billion in cuts over the next decade, but now fears an additional $600 billion or more in cuts that may be imminent if Congress fails to reach an agreement on spending.
“The impact of these cuts would be devastating for the department,” Panetta said in a letter to Senators John McCain, a Republican for Arizona, and Lindsey Graham, a Republican for South Carolina.
He said Congress’ failure to reach an agreement on the budget and its aftermath, the so-called “kidnapping,” would result in 23 percent global cuts and a halt to many new projects.
"Such a large cut, applied in this indiscriminate manner, would make most of our naval and construction projects impossible to execute - you can't buy three-quarters of a ship or a building - and seriously damage other modernization efforts," Panetta wrote to senators.
“We would also be forced to involuntarily remove many of our civilian officials and, because the reduction would be imposed so quickly, it is almost certain that we would have to dismiss civilians in order to meet the target.”
“These changes would break faith with those who maintain our army and seriously damage good disposition.”
The cuts would eventually reach the combat troops, Panetta said.
“While the wartime funding in the Overseas Contingency Operations accounts is not directly affected by the hijacking, war efforts would be negatively affected by serious disruptions to the base budgets,” Panetta warned.
“The hiring of personnel would be reduced, which would lead to delays in contracts and oversight of the contract supporting the war.”
“Payroll staff would be reduced, resulting in delays in payments to suppliers in time of war, and legal and political support would be disrupted.”
The two senators had written to Panetta 10 days ago asking for information about the possible impact of automatic cuts on the Defense Department.
“The consequence of a kidnapping in the Department of Defense would cause a rapid decline of the United States as the world’s leading military power.”
“We are firmly against this draconian action,” the senators said in a joint statement Monday afternoon when they published Panetta’s letter.
“This is not a result with which one can live, and certainly not one that we should impose on ourselves.”
“The kidnapping is a threat to the national security interests of the United States, and it should not be allowed to happen.”
Whether Panetta’s letter and recent warnings from senators will increase pressure for a budget compromise or intensify calls to exempt the Pentagon from the cuts remains to be seen.
Panetta has been increasingly candid about possible cuts, even though he came to a job at the top of the Pentagon with years of budgeting experience in Congress and the White House and knowing he was facing tough decisions.
At a press conference last week, the defense secretary painted a bleak picture of what might be ahead — an army with a shell, but not a core.
"It's a ship without sailors."
"It's a bullet-free brigade."
"It's an air wing without enough trained pilots."
“It’s a paper tiger, an army of barracks, buildings and bombs without enough soldiers trained to fulfill the mission,” Panetta said in his opening words at the Pentagon.
“It is a force that suffers from low morale, poor preparation and is not able to keep up with potential adversaries.”
"In fact, it invites aggression..."
In an appendix to his letters to McCain and Graham, Panetta sets out new details of how the reductions “generate significant operational risks: delay in response time to crises, conflicts and disasters; severely limits our ability to be previously deployed and engaged around the world; and poses an unacceptable risk in future combat operations.”
And Panetta said some of the biggest defense projects could face the axe, including those already being tested and some only in the early stages of planning.
That list includes the F35 Joint Strike Fighter, a planned new bomber, the next-generation ballistic submarine, the new coastal combat ship and the new ground combat vehicle that the Army and Navy need to replace, the humvee.
Stopping further development and testing of the F35 could generate some $80 billion in savings over 10 years, but supporters say it is the vital next step to improve and address potential threats from China and other rivals.
How to Detect a Lie
A look at the most recent headlines tells us how serious and ubiquitous deception and lying are in daily life.
Republican presidential candidate Herman Cain is busy exchanging sexual harassment allegations with several women; each side accuses the other of lying.
Administrators at Pennsylvania State University have been charged with perjury for allegedly hiding reports that a retired football coach was sexually assaulting children.
Last week, French President Nicolas Sarkozy was “picked” with an open microphone claiming to US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is a liar.
Lying has destroyed races and convulsed countries.
New York congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weiner made a mockery of his denials quickly rebuffed by the irrefutable test.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards has been charged with campaign funding violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital relationship.
And, again, no one who lived it will ever forget the media circus unleashed by President Bill Clinton when he lied during his second term about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
Legends about traps in school and university exams are widespread.
There have been instances where teachers have given exam responses to students in order to be better seen in their performance assessments.
Mentors who should be teaching otherwise are sending the message that lying and deceiving are acceptable.
How much deception do we find?
On any given day, studies show that you can be lied to anywhere 10 to 200 times.
That's for sure, many of those lies are pious lies.
Another study showed that strangers lied three times within the first 10 minutes of meeting.
Detecting lies, or “locating lies,” is an essential skill that we must all acquire, for both personal and professional reasons.
Far from being a board game similar to, say, Charada, where the goal is to exclaim, “I have you,” deception detection is a serious branch of knowledge based on scientific data obtained over the past six decades at prestigious universities that have conducted in-depth research projects, especially in psychology and physiology.
One of the results of the research is that the old myths about lying have been refuted.
Liars look into the eyes.
They don’t always stutter, stammer, blush, or worry.
Nor can it be concluded that liars are difficult to detect or unmask.
A trained lie detector can come to the truth by learning about the structure of the statement, microfacial expressions, question formation, and timing.
I spent several years probing scientific discoveries about deception in the vast and ever-emerging body of knowledge, and it was clear that deception detection is a modern technique that is easy to learn and helps navigate our complex world – especially if your professional responsibilities include hiring, interviewing, or managing negotiations.
Good liars have the ability to read well to others, making them feel comfortable, managing their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how others perceive them.
We know from research that extroverts lie more than introverts, that men tell more "self-oriented lies," while women tell more "other-oriented lies" -- usually to protect someone's feelings -- that married people lie to their partners less often than unmarried people (but the lies they usually tell) tend to be "huge".
We also know that if you are perceived as an evildoer, others will feel less guilty about lying to you.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, observe the usual behavior of the subject.
This is called “creating a baseline.”
It helps to provide benchmarks to then measure changes.
Observe the subject’s posture, laughter, and vocal characteristic.
It’s best to know if someone normally kicks all the time so as not to make unfair accusations when you see their feet kicking in the middle of the meeting.
Next, look for deceptive, verbal and nonverbal behavioral groups.
Consider these behavioral groups as warning signs, not as proof of deception.
People who cheat can freeze their upper body by trying to remember their story, they can point their feet at the door, lean toward an exit, change their posture significantly, or exhibit a “post-interview relief” — that exaggerated sigh of relief and change of posture once all the difficult questions are over.
Often interrogators falsely make it appear that the interview is over just to seek that post-interview relief.
Also pay attention to the subject’s vocabulary.
Scott Peterson screwed up to the bottom and used the past while claiming his murdered wife was alive, launching a nationwide search for her.
People who cheat can also use a distancing language: “I didn’t have sex with that woman... Miss Lewinsky” or repeat a difficult question entirely.
The most common verbal indicators are subtle.
Someone can use a lot of "restrictive language" when answering a difficult question: "Well... to tell you the truth... as far as I can... to my understanding."
This makes the response a perception rather than a fact and is often a wake-up call.
There is no magic formula for detecting lies, but developing skills to discover deception is possible.
These skills will improve the chances of anyone to avoid being victimized by scam artists in their professional and personal lives.
Controversial Pipeline Plan Deflected After Threat of U.S. Delay in Approval
Days after the Obama administration threatened to delay approval of a planned pipeline from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico — infuriating unions, while appeasing environmentalists — the company seeking to build the pipeline says it is ready to redirect the project to reroute it.
TransCanada said Monday night it will move the planned pipeline out of the ecologically sensitive Sandhills area in Nebraska, and is confident the project will win approval.
The company announced the decision at a news conference at the Nebraska Capitol.
TransCanada executive Alex Pourbax says the company maintains its confidence that the pipeline will eventually be approved, although it does have a different route.
This comes after the State Department announced last week that it would delay the decision for a federal permit for the project until new potential routes are studied that avoid the Sandhills areas of Nebraska and the Ogallala aquifer, a vast groundwater supply.
“This is a real road to progress,” Rep. Lee Terry, a Republican from Nebraska, told Fox News.
The new environmental review ordered by the State Department may set aside any decision until 2013, after next year’s election, though officials denied the policy was involved in the decision.
Obama, in a written statement last week, described the decision as the State Department’s request, and expressed his full support to them.
The 1,700-kilometre pipeline would stretch from Canada to the Gulf of Mexico.
It would take 700,000 barrels per day from the province of Alberta to refineries in Texas.
To do this, it would have to cross six states.
It is hated by environmentalists, but loved by working groups, who have bet on the estimate of 20,000 jobs linked to the pipeline.
But Nebraska lawmakers opposed to the plan are weighing legislation to force a move away from the Sandhills region and the Ogallala aquifer, the largest source of drinking water and irrigation.
The State Department’s current environmental impact study found that the project posed only limited adverse environmental impacts, but the energy industry source said the department’s inspector general has ordered an independent test of the review process, focusing on two issues.
One is whether TransCanada’s hired lobbyist Paul Elliot, who was Hillary Clinton’s campaign adviser in 2008, represents a conflict of interest for the program.
The other is whether a firm that was hired to direct the original studio was an inappropriate choice because it was tied to TransCanada.
Patti LaBelle sued for allegedly causing a child to vomit in fear
A New York family claims disco diva Patti LaBelle behaved like a madwoman in the lobby of her Manhattan building, terrifying her little daughter to the point that she vomited in fear.
The "Lady Marmalade" singer's diatribe scared 18-month-old Genevieve Monk so much that she suffered "personality changes, sleep disorders" and "increased her fear of strangers," her family says at the Manhattan Supreme Court.
It was November 10th of last year when tramboy Kevin Monk, his wife, Roseanna, a kindergarten teacher, and Genevieve were preparing to go on a family trip.
While Kevin Monk was taking the car, Roseanna Monk walked down to the lobby of the Riverside Boulevard building, carrying her luggage, carrying Genevieve.
Roseanna Monk said she stood near the door and put her daughter on the floor for a moment.
“Someone came up from behind and said, ‘You know what your daughter is doing?’ I said, ‘Yes,’ and I went to get her,” he said.
LaBelle angrily admonished the pregnant woman.
"He said in an aggressive tone, 'I shouldn't have left your daughter near the door,'" Roseanna Monk said.
“I said, ‘I have no interest in what you say or think.’
He became angry and began to use bad words - the word C and the word J aloud...
I had a bottle of water and he started throwing the water out of the bottle on me."
He said Genevieve got hysterical.
"I said to this woman, 'Look what you've done to my daughter,'" the girl's mother said.
LaBelle rushed over the mother -- who was still holding Genevieve -- and had to be restrained by her surroundings and pulled back to a car waiting for her, Roseanna Monk said.
The little girl was crying so hard she threw up, he added.
Later, the family sent a note apologizing to LaBelle, but received no response.
LaBelle’s lawyer and representatives did not return the calls to comment on what happened.
The lawsuit seeks unspecified damages, but the family’s lawyer, Sam Davis, said he took the case for free and that the family plans to donate all the money it gets to a support association for children with cancer.
“The purpose is to hold Patti LaBelle accountable for her conduct,” Davis said.
“That kind of behavior is completely unacceptable, especially when you address a kindergarten teacher who is carrying an 18-month-old child in her arms.”
Climate Adversity Has Slowed the Economy
During the first year of management of Mario López Valdez, in Sinaloa, unemployment and informality have increased, foreign investment has fallen and the economy has contracted
2011 is a year that will be remembered in the economic history of Sinaloa, it is the first year of government of Mario López Valdez, self-styled change, which generated great expectations regarding the advances in the economy, but given the climate adversity of the beginning of the year, there is no growth, instead there is a deterioration in the main indicators of economic development.
The low temperatures of February, in addition to causing million-dollar losses for the agricultural sector, limited the possibilities of the state economy to grow, caused a contraction of economic activity in general of 3.6 percent in the first half of the year, mainly justified by the historic fall of 31.16 percent in agriculture, which affected the dynamism of the other economic sectors.
According to the frost damage report issued by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, 582,835 hectares were damaged, of which 78.03 percent suffered total damage and the remaining 21.07 percent had partial damage, the main crops affected were vegetables, corn and chickpeas.
The fall in economic activity has generated, until November, a steady increase in unemployment in the state, according to the National Institute of Statistics and Geography, the rate of unemployment in the state during the first three quarters of the year was observed an accelerated growth, since while from January to March 55 thousand 053 people from Sinaloa were unemployed, with a rate of 4.53 percent of the Economically Active Population, for the second quarter it was 5.
Less liquidity
Unemployment in Sinaloa during the year is multifactorial, for the economist Gerardo López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences of the UAS, the growth of unemployment can be explained indirectly, depending on the actions that have been taken by public policy.
“What we are seeing is an increase in unemployment that has to do with several factors, including the loss of liquidity in the market due to a restriction of resources by the legislation that was passed in Congress to combat money laundering, and for people who grab dollars in an illicit way it is not easy for them to work them, invest them and use them in something,” he said.
Migration Detained
López Cervantes pointed out that in the increase in unemployment there is also a demographic factor.
“The number of people who leave the state looking for work abroad, in the United States has been restricted, firstly because of the difficulties of entering, and secondly because entering have also many difficulties to find work, those people are staying and are demanding sources of work here in the state, which causes unemployment to rise,” he said.
Informality
The analysis of the labor market in Sinaloa is aggravated by considering the high level of informality that predominates among working conditions, according to the INEGI, 60.38 percent of the employed population in the state works without being paid as a worker before any social security institution.
In addition to unemployment and informality, another of the labor lags of the state are low wages, the entity has the lowest wages in the country, according to the records of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labor and Social Welfare.
The average monthly income of Sinaloan workers was, until September, 5,352 pesos, well below the national average, located at 7,375 pesos.
Contraction of FDI
In addition to the fall in economic activity and the increase in unemployment, during 2011 there was the largest decrease in foreign direct investment in the last 10 years, according to the Ministry of Economy from January to June, the state FDI totaled $ 630,697, which represents a fall of 87.74 percent compared to the 5 million 143,312 dollars registered during the same period of the previous year.
For its part, the Ministry of Economic Development of the state government accounts for a total investment of 17,280 million pesos in the year, mainly from companies in the tertiary sector.
The Debt
Given the scenario of economic contraction, the state government requested in July to the state congress the approval of a loan for 3 billion pesos, same that would be destined the investment in infrastructure projects in the 18 municipalities, with the purpose of reviving the economy, the approval of the local congress was for an amount of 2,600 million pesos, and until November they have not observed the benefits of the indebtedness in any sector of the economy.
Reactions
For representatives of the business sector, the first year of government of Mario López Valdés shows a lack of management capacity of the government.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of the Transformation Industry, said that during 2011 there was a lack of harmonization of the wills of the different sectors, including the state government itself.
"The performance of the economy in Sinaloa during this year has been really very poor, we have to work intensely to recover the ground that we lost in this year, in 2012 we have to redouble our efforts, it was missing to align the effort of all and above all the good march already synchronized of this new government team, we hope that next year will be much better," he said.
Economic Slowness
Loredo López said events such as the frosts at the beginning of the year halted the state economy and restricted its performance and growth.
"The low economic flow is the product of several events, including frosts, one of the main effects has been a slow economy that does not turn around fast enough to generate an economic dynamism that allows us to have an acceptable level of flow in processes, products and services and therefore, at the end of the year we are closing well below the expectations we had," he said.
Redefining the vocation
For Teodoro Salazar Uriarte, president of the Employers’ Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, said that it is necessary to prosecute the state towards productive activities of greater dynamism.
"In general terms we have observed that work has been done, we believe that it is necessary to develop a long-term program in which the vocation and economic direction of the state is redefined, because it is important that the full potential of the material and human resource that Sinaloa has is detonated," he said.
Work to do
The president of Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision for the future that better guides the Government’s efforts.
"In general terms I would say that the government has been striving to give good results in different areas, in terms of economic development there are some advances but it is important that a long-term program is developed," he said.
He noted that the current administration has shown progress in its way of conducting public policy.
"There are elements that allow us to say that the government is being more inclusive, what I can say is that there is work done and I think the government is aware that there is work to be done," he said.
