Corte validates "analog blackout" in Mexico in 2015
Replacing analog signals with digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years
The Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) dismissed the constitutional controversies brought by the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies against the presidential decree that advances the so-called "analog blackout" from 2021 to 2015, because they did not meet the eight votes necessary to invalidate it.
A minority of four ministers, including the president of the Court, Juan Silva Meza, considered that President Felipe Calderón did not exceed his powers by issuing the decree detailing the actions to be taken to make the transition to digital terrestrial television.
With that result, the constitutional controversy promoted by the Senate of the Republic, was dismissed for not reaching the qualified majority of eight votes for the Court to rule on the constitutionality or unconstitutionality of the decree, and it remains in force.
The draft ruling, drafted by Minister Olga Sánchez Cordero, proposed declaring the decree unconstitutional, because the regulation of radio and television matters is a faculty reserved by law to the Federal Telecommunications Commission (Cofetel), in contravention of the principles of hierarchical subordination and reservation of law.
In favor of the project voted only Zaldívar, Jorge Mario Pardo, Margarita Luna and Sánchez Cordero herself.
With this argument, both the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies promoted two constitutional controversies to challenge the decree, and by admitting the demands, Minister Sánchez Cordero suspended the application of the decree and all the actions arranged for the digital transition.
The plenary of ministers also decided to dismiss the demand lodged by the Chamber of Deputies, without entering into the discussion of the project, also in charge of Minister Sánchez Cordero.
In his speech, the minister president said he did not agree with the arguments of the project, in the sense that the federal Executive cannot structure through general rules the measures for the public administration to prepare.
“I also do not consider that doing so would affect the autonomy of the regulatory body,” and recalled that the planning of public policies in strategic areas such as the telecommunications sector correspond to the federal Executive, who has a constitutional mandate, the State rectory.
The replacement of analog signals by digital signals is one of the most important changes the world has undergone in recent years, and it translates into a better use of the radio spectrum, better signal quality and more channels.
To postpone the change, he said, would be to postpone the benefits of digitalization, which involves a decision of public interest, which does not have only a technical dimension, "because it covers economic, social, political and national security issues."
These issues, he stressed, "require the operation of the entire system established, in accordance with the principle of state economic rectory, encompasses a group of powers that the Constitution leads to the power of the state executive."
He recalled that a large number of countries around the world have already completed the digital transition, and have done so through the Executive, despite having highly specialized technical bodies.
It cannot be concluded that the Executive, in issuing the contested decree, invades in some way the sphere of competence of the Congress, since the observance of the laws issued by the Legislative is being provided in the administrative sphere, he said.
They analyze the possibility of a "vote by vote" count in Michoacán
According to the data released by the PREP the difference between first and second place of the election of governor is just 27 percent, still without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,74 total minutes.
The possibility of the "vote for vote" count is a reality as far as this year's electoral process in Michoacán is concerned, where according to data released by the Preliminary Election Results Program (PREP) the difference between first and second place in the governor's election is just 27 percent, even without counting the votes corresponding to 879 of the 6,74 total minutes.
In this regard, the president of the General Council of the Electoral Institute of Michoacán (IEM), María de los <0xC3><0x81>ngeles Llanderal Zaragoza, recalled that a few days ago, just on November 9, the electoral body approved a series of guidelines in order to harmonize the local norms with the federal reform in electoral matters.
As will be recalled, Michoacán did not approve its Political Constitution or its State Electoral Code or its Electoral Justice Law, since the State Congress approved the reforms shortly before the legal deadline for them to enter into force in the current electoral process and Governor Leonel Godoy Rangel omitted its publication within the deadlines provided for in the Law of the Official State Newspaper, with the argument of
On November 9, the Supreme Court of Justice of the Nation (SCJN) resolved the constitutional controversy promoted by the local legislature and described as "invalid and illegal" the vote of the state president to constitutional reforms, since he has no right to "sanction or veto them".
Interviewed about the possibility of "voting by vote", María de los <0xC3><0x81>ngeles Llanderal explained that thanks to the approval of the corresponding guidelines by the General Council of the IEM it will be possible to carry out partial and total counts of the vote by the local electoral body.
In this way, the partial count of votes, of one or more electoral packages, may take place in the event that: the results of the minutes do not coincide; there is no record of scrutiny and counting in the file of the box or does not operate in the possession of the president of the same; or, when there are errors or obvious alterations of the minutes.
In addition, the total count of the vote received in all the polling stations may be carried out when there is an indication that the difference between the alleged candidate who won the election in question and the one who obtained the second place in the poll is equal to or less than one percentage point; provided that at the beginning of the session there is the express request of the representative of the party and / or coalition that applied for the second of the nominated candidates.
The total count of the vote may also be made if at the end of the ordinary count it is established that the difference between the candidate allegedly winning and the one in second place is equal to or less than one percentage point, provided that there is the express request of the representative of the political party whose candidate was in second place, in which case the electoral packages that have been subject to partial count will be excluded.
It should be mentioned that in this situation is the election of Morelia, where according to the PREP the difference between the first and second place is only 0.16 percent, although without counting the votes of 129 of the 923 total minutes.
