The new Italian government will be formed on Wednesday.
The prime minister, Mario Monti, will meet tomorrow with the president of Italy to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put that country on the verge of economic disaster.
Italian Prime Minister Mario Monti will meet with Italy's president on Wednesday to present the new government that will face a crisis that has put Italy on the verge of economic disaster and endangered the entire eurozone.
A statement from the presidential palace announced that Monti, appointed on Sunday, will meet with President Giorgio Napolitano on Wednesday to confirm that he can form a government.
It is expected to introduce a cabinet composed mostly of technocrats, although it is unclear when the new executive will take office.
Monti said he would present to the president the outcome of his talks with political parties in his bid to form a government.
"I want to confirm my absolute confidence in our country's ability to overcome this difficult phase," he told reporters.
Monti did not explicitly say he would be able to form a government but the tone of his comments indicated that the obstacles had been overcome.
The “framework is now well outlined,” he added.
Monti has completed the process of forming a government in less than three days, much less than normal, as Italy battles a political and financial crisis that has pushed its debt costs to unsustainable levels.
The new administration headed by former EU commissioner Monti must approve a tough austerity package demanded by European leaders to regain hit-and-run confidence in Italy.
Underlining pressure on Monti to hurry, market instability put the performance of Italian 10-year BTP bonds above 7 percent, the level at which Greece and Ireland were forced to be rescued.
Emma Marcegaglia, the leader of the Italian employers' union Confindustria, told reporters after meeting with Monti: "We said we would support this government very much."
We believe that this Government is the last chance for Italy to emerge from this emergency situation.
Monti's chances of success were boosted considerably by the support of Silvio Berlusconi's PDL party, which the crisis forced to resign on Saturday.
"We believe that Professor Monti's efforts are destined to have a good result," Angelino Alfano, secretary of the centre-right party, told reporters.
The support of the PDL, Italy’s largest party, is significant because so far many of its members had opposed the technocrat-majority government that is forming Monti.
Parliamentary support
Monti’s new government must have strong parliamentary support to implement what are likely to be unpopular austerity reforms.
Any blockage or delay in their efforts could provoke a new and devastating attack on financial markets.
The Italian association of foreign banks added to the pressure by warning that a Monti failure would be a disaster.
On Monday, Monti began consultations with political parties, trade unions and business groups, as well as youth and women’s organizations.
It will end its round of meetings on Tuesday night.
Monti was appointed on Sunday by Napolitano, who has enabled an extremely rapid transition in response to the crisis.
After a brief respite at the end of last week, when it became clear that Berlusconi would step down, Italian debt costs have now returned to critical levels amid uncertainty over whether the new prime minister will succeed.
Rescuing Italy, with a public debt of 1.8 trillion euros, would be too much for the eurozone’s current financial defenses.
Monti has said his administration should last until the next elections, scheduled for 2013, despite widespread predictions that politicians will only give him time to implement reforms before he advances the elections.
Monti has said he would like to include politicians in his cabinet, but the big parties insist it should be made up only of technicians, a sign of his fears over a process forced by financial pressure.
Political sources pointed out that mutual mistrust and disagreements between the parties are complicating the attempt to include political figures.
