I have been in Costa Rica only once and on vacation; it is such a beautiful country and I think we will be able to stay a few days there.
So we’re excited to bring our music there.
I ask because there is a kind of devotion to the band, the fans live with intensity the days before.
What do you say to your most fervent followers?
Thank you for staying by our side through all these years.
It took us almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica; thank you for waiting so long and we regret that it took us so long to get there.
Some people even already refer to their concert as the biggest show of the year.
Does that add a bit of pressure to your visit?
Some of the biggest shows we’ve played over the last 21 years have happened over the last couple of weeks.
We played a couple of gigantic shows in Sao Paulo and hopefully that put us in shape for this concert in Costa Rica.
We’re really looking forward to playing there.
We love that country, we love surfing and the jungle; for both, Costa Rica is among the best in the world.
How did they discover Costa Rica and its surfing waves?
We have many friends who are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo and the waves there are amazing.
My friends were always going to surf in Costa Rica and Nicaragua, along with Mexico, are great places to surf; this is how we learned, through people who love surfing.
Watching the tour, they’ve been delivering huge shows with lots of songs.
What have you planned for your presentation in Costa Rica?
Since we have never played there before, then we have no restrictions on what we can do.
We will try to give the best possible show with a good variety of songs; we will try to play a couple of songs from each album and give our fans a good and diverse repertoire.
You never repeat the repertoire.
What's the reason for this?
I think it’s partly because we have nine records and we can play more than 120 songs and everyone likes different songs, so it’s hard to choose which songs to play each night.
When we have two or three songs in the repertoire that we haven’t played for a while, that keeps us focused and also keeps us surprised because it reminds us of the reasons why we liked those songs and that we might have forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and therefore I think it also makes it more interesting for people.
With this tour, they are celebrating 20 years of career.
Looking back, is it hard to believe everything they’ve achieved?
Yes, absolutely.
“First of all, I don’t think any of us imagined we’d be in a great rock band and having done it for over 20 years makes it look like a dream.
We continue to count our blessings and are very excited that we can continue to make music together.
We all love and love creating music.
We are fortunate to go to places in the world that we have always wanted to go to.
Things couldn't be better for us.
What did it mean for you to have been a fundamental part of the rise of grunge?
It’s always been an honor to be part of that big band.
We are very friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising when a movement arises from a group of friends and it is something uncommon.
From time to time, a band from a city emerges, but it is much stranger when five or ten bands leave the same city at the same time.
We are proud and honored to be part of the Seattle group.
We still play with some of them from time to time.
Last year, we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and we were in Canada with Mudhoney, we saw Soundgarden on their tour, so we’re lucky to be friends with all of them still and we’re honored to be part of that Seattle sound that emerged.
It’s also very strange that a band like yours stays together and with the same members for so long.
Yes, four of us have been together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago, which, by itself, is much longer than many bands last.
Firstly, I think we are all lucky to be still alive, and secondly, we all care about each other.
We are all very close friends and, thanks to that, musical avenues have also been opened that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
We trust each other with each other’s music and it couldn’t be better.
Your relationship with the word fame has not been simple; however, thanks to your success, you have been able to do whatever you want.
How do you find a balance?
As we have grown, it has been easier to find a balance.
We make sure you don’t be on tour too much because it’s easy to fall into that game of the big crowds and people who love your music.
As long as you remember that people are there for the music, that reminds you that you must respect the music and what brought it, without getting tempted to be famous and be a rock star, something that none of us really cares about.
How do you remember your other Mother Love Bone project?
I think we wrote very good songs and it was great at first.
We were a band for almost three years and never released a record until after Andy (Andrew Woods) died.
There was a lot of frustration because it lasted so long and the most important thing is that we are still very friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who started in the band with us and when I hear a song or see a photo I think of the amazing person Andy was and how it made me laugh, it was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh, talk about music and football and much more.
He was an amazing human being and we missed him.
The national band Las Robertas will be in charge of opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose her for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos with several proposals and that was the band we liked the most, so we are eager to see what Las Robertas can offer live and should be very entertaining.
Why do they always change the lyrics of Yellow Ledbetter live?
That's a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), so I don't know.
He sings it and I think he does it with the first thing that comes to his mind.
As a bassist, what are your influences?
There are so many.
Among the first ones I think of are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I love.
How has Pearl Jam managed to keep grunge relevant even though it is no longer a fashion?
I think all of us always feel a little disconnected from the word grunge.
When I think about it, it reminds me of the bands I mentioned before, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all that came up at the same time, and, if there’s relevance now, I think it’s something wonderful because it’s music that’s worth listening to and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever.
At first, his music had a darker content and now it has become more positive.
What is the reason for this change?
It’s interesting because I think there are a couple of songs on the new album that might seem lighter, but there are also songs, like The End or Just Breathe that qualify as very dark songs though they may sound a little bit positive.
With both of them, when Ed touched me, I cried when I heard them and they are deeply dark songs.
I think when you grow up and there’s some trauma in your life and you lose a family member or a friend, those things start to influence your art and your music and those two songs, undoubtedly, represent that to me.
Also, I think you can be a happy person and still be able to make music that is dark.
Peru:
Fujimori is hospitalized again for medical examinations
Former President Alberto Fujimori was admitted Tuesday to a public hospital to be evaluated for the loss of muscle strength he has in his legs, his GP said.
Fujimori, 72, who is serving a 25-year prison sentence for human rights violations committed during his administration (1990-2000), suffers from several ailments, including a cancer of the tongue for which he has been operated on four times and which he remains under control.
Congressman Alejandro Aguinaga, who is his personal physician, told Channel N television that Fujimori will be evaluated for three days at the National Institute of Neoplastic Diseases to determine the reason for the pain and loss of strength of his lower limbs.
Aguinaga commented that in his opinion Fujimori would be a candidate to obtain the benefit of the pardon for humanitarian reasons, however, he said he does not want it because he knows he is innocent.
He was operated on four times for cancer of the tongue, has a weight loss of 18 kilos to which other pathologies have been added such as severe erosive gastritis, cyst of the pancreas, kidney stones, hypertension and circulatory problems in the legs, the doctor listed.
Fujimori has been serving incarceration since September 2007 in the National Directorate of Special Operations of the police.
In April 2009, he was sentenced to 25 years in prison for the deaths of 25 people at the hands of an army annihilation squad that operated clandestinely in the early years of his government.
Mujica travels to Mexico to strengthen political ties
An official delegation, led by Uruguayan President José Mujica, and composed of several ministers and businessmen, will begin a visit to Mexico on Tuesday in order to expand trade between the two nations and address political issues in the region.
Mujica will meet next Wednesday with his Mexican counterpart, Felipe Calderón, the highest point of an extensive agenda of meetings with political, commercial and a meeting with the community of Uruguayans living in Mexico, according to the agenda disseminated by the Uruguayan Presidency.
The meeting between the two presidents, in the city of Guadalajara, will be "proper for the exchange of information on all that are political issues between the two nations", as published by the presidency of the South American country on its website.
According to local media, Mujica would seek to get Calderon to support Uruguay in the incident with France that arose when the French president, Nicolas Sarkozy, included the South American country in a list of tax havens, at the G20 meeting in the French city of Cannes.
In his speech, Sarkozy threatened to exclude from the international community those countries that remain tax havens, a statement that provoked the rejection of Uruguay and the call for consultation with its ambassador in the European country.
Mexico has been chairing the G20 since November, a group of the world’s most powerful emerging and developed countries, and has an agreement with the South American country since January this year to exchange tax information in order to avoid double taxation.
The Uruguayan government has tried in recent years to expedite the implementation of tax exchange agreements in order to get out of the "gray list" of the Organization for Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD), formed by countries that did not implement all the international standards of cooperation in tax matters.
In terms of trade, Mexico and Uruguay have a Free Trade Agreement (FTA) in place since 2004 that has increased the exchange of goods between both nations.
The mustache plumber passes the three dimensions with "Super Mario 3D Land"
Super Mario has fought, tirelessly, over 25 years to save Princess Peach from the clutches of the evil Bowser, but never before had he done so in three dimensions: in "Super Mario 3D Land" he will fight for the girl's love in stereoscopic technology.
The title, which arrives this month in stores around the world, has been designed from the outset to take advantage of the features of the Nintendo 3DS handheld console, which allows you to play in three dimensions without the use of glasses.
“Mario is the character who has to say how stereoscopy without glasses should work,” said Omar <0xC3><0x81>lvarez, the head of specialized press at Nintendo in Spain, during the presentation of the video game in Madrid.
<0xC3><0x81>lvarez noted that "Super Mario 3D Land" is "the first Nintendo video game originally intended for that support", as hits such as "Star Fox 64 3D" or "Zelda: Ocarine of time 3D" were adaptations of existing titles.
The Nintendo spokesman has argued that, despite being in 3D, "Super Mario 3D Land" is an "accessible" video game that allows you to enjoy a fast and smooth game.
Alvarez has stated that "Super Mario 3D Land" contains two games in one: the first part is "simple" to hook less skilled users.
Once overcome, the more experienced will be able to give a "second turn" to the levels of play, which this time present greater difficulty.
In addition, users will be able to choose in real time between an "aggressive D" or one that only affects the depth of the action, but it will be necessary to play in three dimensions to be able to overcome the different challenges and "not succumb to optical illusions".
This incursion of Super Mario in the three dimensions also implies the return of the character to a portable console, a fact that was not produced since 2005.
In this video game Nintendo nods to the fans of the saga and repeats the formula of the success of the previous installments, consisting in that the plumber of the mustache will have to travel platforms mined with dangers in order to free Princess Peach.
Although the player will find novelties in the movements, environments, costumes and enemies and also a Luigi "playable".
Colom backs Portillo’s extradition to the United States
President <0xC3><0x81>lvaro Colom announced on Tuesday that he has proceeded with the extradition of former governor Alfonso Portillo to the United States to answer for the $70 million laundering conspiracy.
Thus ends the process for Guatemala to respond to the request of the northern country that claimed Portillo to judge him there.
At a press conference, Colom said his decision was based on the independence of the judiciary and executive powers, taking into account that a sentencing court had already ordered the extradition.
During his tenure, he said, he "did not get his hands on" court decisions and proceeded with all the extraditions he has known.
In addition to Portillo, Sergio Ruano Marroquín will be extradited, for murder and serious injuries, and Edgar Estrada Morales and Víctor Estrada Paredes, both for drug trafficking.
What Colom did was an executive procedure after all the judicial and constitutional bodies had been exhausted to prosecute the former president between 2000 and 2004.
According to decisions of the Fifth Criminal Court and the Constitutional Court (CC), Portillo must be extradited once he has settled his legal situation in Guatemala and his human rights are guaranteed.
Portillo was acquitted of the embezzlement of Q120 million in the Ministry of Defense when he was president, which was the process that preceded the extradition, but the Public Prosecutor’s Office appealed and reactivated the case.
Trinijove has helped 6,000 young people at risk
The entity was born to prevent the drop in the marginality of untrained children
The balance of the first 25 years of life of the social support entity Trinijove is important: 6,000 young people at risk of exclusion have received help to overcome a difficult situation throughout this quarter century.
Added to this are the hundreds of jobs currently created for this social group.
The anniversary served yesterday to take stock of an event held in the former factory complex of Fabra i Coats attended by more than 300 people.
Trinijove was born in the neighborhood of Trinitat Vella in 1986 with the aim of helping young people with little training, without work, with problems of degradation or in a situation of falling into marginalization.
The celebration of yesterday in Sant Andreu concentrated a large number of leaders of entities and institutions that in these 25 years have collaborated with the association.
The varied political representation, in full electoral time, showed the unity of the work carried out by Trinijove.
Together with the president of the Generalitat, Artur Mas, and his predecessor Jordi Pujol, the former socialist education councillor, Ernest Maragall, and the former mayor and current ecosocialist councillor Ricard Gomà attended the event.
The current Minister of Social Welfare and Family, Josep Lluís Cleries, and the general director of the social work of La Caixa, Jaume Lanaspa, also attended the large hall of La Fabra i Coats.
Mas said that Trinijove was born in a very difficult time and that the current one is too, but added that the work done so far "is a good basis".
The president set Trinijove as an example for knowing how to fight against bad circumstances and for giving hope to people in difficulty.
"The crisis is not something new for the entity and for the work it does," he said.
Evicted an occupied estate where macrofestivals were held
The invaders had seized 11 of the 13 floors of the building, in Balmes, 51
The 12 occupants left the estate at noon yesterday without offering resistance
Everything seems to indicate that the nightmare lived by the neighbors of 51 de la calle de Balmes has come to an end.
Twelve people voluntarily left yesterday noon the property they were illegally occupying, and where they were organizing macro parties that despaired the neighborhood, by court order and without the need for police intervention.
When the operation was over, the door lock was changed to prevent the situation from repeating itself.
“From now on there will be an access control,” the administrator said.
The squats, which had invaded 11 of the 13 floors of the building -the rest are inhabited-, took away all the electrical installation and part of the water, in addition to painting the walls and leaving waste of all kinds, especially cans of alcoholic beverages.
The first three floors were the scene of the crowded parties, which lasted up to two days and despaired the tenants.
Next to the building is a nightclub, Balmes 51, which has also been damaged.
Its owner, Maria Pantinat, told Europa Press that since the building was occupied the business has fallen by 80%.
The owner of the disco says that the invaders of the estate made unfair competition, since they sold the glasses for three euros, while in the disco they are worth 10.
In addition, the owner of the leisure venue had had to respond to complaints about noise, while, according to him, the inconvenience was caused not by the customers of the disco, but by the inhabitants of the occupied house and, above all, by the attendees of the parties that were organized there, which had increased their frequency and intensity in recent weeks, according to the angry neighbors of the area.
The head of the club explained that the inconvenience was so great that he even reached an agreement with the owner of the property and nine months ago he "forgives" the rent.
The Guardia Urbana also confirmed that in recent weeks it had received more complaints from neighbors about the situation.
The president of the municipal group of the PP in the city, Alberto Fernández Díaz, had last week called for "immediately evict the property to end the problems of coexistence and civility that produce neighbors, as well as the degradation of the area".
The popular leader explained that before the summer there was only one floor of the building occupied, but over the last few months the squatters had been entering all the floors of the building and in almost all the floors, and in some there have even been robberies.
In this sense, he added that, "it is necessary to end impunity and be forceful against the incivility that has been generated in the estate."
Also yesterday, the Mossos evicted a building in Nou Barris.
At 3.30 p.m. police headed to 35 rue de Mont-ral after receiving a call from a neighbour who had observed four people entering the building.
All four were arrested at the time.
Park or mountain?
The architects agree on the opportunity of the call beyond controversies about fees
The municipal contest on the 16 doors reopens the debate on the role of Collserola in Barcelona
In the mid-1980s, at the height of the now-defunct Corporación Metropolitana de Barcelona (CMB), this Administration printed some promotional pasquines of Collserola.
The booklet defined the mountain as the great park of metropolitan Barcelona.
What’s more, it was accompanied by a comparison, in figures, with New York’s Central Park.
With the death of the CMB, in 1987, the park once again became, in the imagination of many, the upper limit of Barcelona, being the Catalan capital of the few that are not oriented on the north-south axis but up (mountain) -down (sea).
The classification of Collserola as a natural park reflects this idea.
The reference was no longer Central Park but Yellowstone, with wild boars in the role of the Yogi bear.
These were until, in September, the city council called a mega-competition consisting of 16 contests for as many gateways to Collserola.
A door refers to the idea of a park, no doubt.
Either that or someone intends to put doors in the field.
The question arises alone: Collserola, park or mountain?
The contest, both for its purely organizational aspect and for what it supposes of reflection on the city is the topic of conversation among all the Barcelona architects.
It’s almost already a recurring theme when two members of this ancient caste of chosen ones recognize each other in an elevator.
And this fact gives rise, precisely, to one of the few coincidences between what three Barcelona architects think, and university professors, who have presented themselves.
Miguel Roldán, Daniel M<0xC3><0xB2>dol and Marta Bayona: the contest is timely.
For Roldán, after addressing the coastal front "it becomes necessary" to discuss "the mountain front", since the speech of Ildefons Cerdà, that of the green apples, has not been carried out.
"It is fitting to start from the basis that the largest park in Barcelona is the beach.
Among other things because of its great accessibility.
Collserola is more complex, "says the architect for whom the title of "doors of Collserola" encloses a "lexical trap": we should not think of them "as accesses to a park, but the delimitation of areas where you have to act".
M<0xC3><0xB2>dol, like Roldán and Bayona with experience in the urban world, describes the proposal as an "intellectual challenge" with "some dangers".
Dangers derived from the "uncertainty that it is today to project the public space" after the experience lived in the 80s and that had in the area of the Forum "su canto del cisne".
The first fear is the very delimitation of borders on where it can be built.
“To limit something is to fix already the next step,” that is, its overtaking.
"We must think of new urban planning instruments, because the current ones [in reference to the Metropolitan General Plan (PGM)] can give rise to real disasters."
More limited to the question, M<0xC3><0xB2>dol thinks that, simplifying, the Valls slope of Collserola "can be understood as a park, that of Barcelona, no", for a purely topographical question.
M<0xC3><0xB2>dol recalls that there is already a work done by the Patronat de Collserola that "must not fall into disrepair", although he appreciates the opportunity that the city council offers his guild to intervene in this project "from the first moment".
And even more, he understands that the proximity of the mountain to the city is the safe passage that allows architects to enter the debate, but "doubt" about whether it is this technical profile that should lead the multidisciplinary teams ("all a success", he points out) that have had to create: "Architects should be just a tool".
Bayona suggests that the answer to the question that gives title to this piece is complex, because in the bases of the contest there is a lack of a global vision of Collserola: "There have been called 16 cross-sectional contests -he says- in the mountain-sea sense, but there is no longitudinal reading, that sees and understands the area as a whole".
This causes, at least in your case, that you have chosen to participate in the 16 contests.
Otherwise, a project for one of the doors can collide in program and definition with that of the architect of the door next door.
In his opinion, however, the city council should ensure that the strip immediately above the Ronda de Dalt should provide, in its entirety, an area of equipment that will make a smooth transition between the city and the green.
Casino forgives Jonás Larrazábal and will go free
After 72 days of rooting, the legal representative of Casino Red granted the pardon to the brother of the mayor of Monterrey of the process that was followed by alleged blackmail
After 72 days in prison, Manuel Jonás Larrazábal will be released after the legal representative of Casino Red granted him a pardon before the Second District Criminal Court, which is pursuing a process for blackmail against the brother of the mayor of Monterrey.
After the attack on the Casino Royale, the owner of the Casino Red, Sergio Gil García, made public a series of photographs and videos in which allegedly Manuel Jonás demanded the payment of an economic fee for the regiomontano city council to allow the clandestine operation of the bookmaker.
After the public complaint, the state prosecutor’s office opened a criminal case against the brother of the Panista mayor and on September 2 he was arrested and held for 30 days.
After four hours before the Public Prosecutor’s Office 3 in Property Crimes, he was transferred to the Casa de Arraigo 1, located in the Old Quarter of the state capital.
He remained there for the next 49 days after a second injunction was issued after the Public Prosecutor ' s Office dismissed the bribery and organized crime offences.
On 19 October, he was transferred to Cadereyta prison for allegedly blackmailing the owners of Casino Red with 1.5 million pesos; however, he remained only a few hours in the medium-security prison since death threats existed against him.
The authorities allowed him to continue the trial interned in the municipal cells of San Nicolás de los Garza.
On October 25, he was given an arrest warrant by the secretary of the Second District Criminal Court, Jorge Yánez, who said that after almost two months of investigations, enough evidence was verified to determine Jonás’ guilt, such as the charge of 1.5 million pesos to the representatives of the bookmaker in exchange for allowing the operation of the same.
This Monday, the legal representative of Casino Red, Víctor Aldo García Gómez, went to the judge José Luis Pecina to ask for forgiveness for the brother of the royal mayor; so in the coming hours he could regain his freedom.
During the legal diligence, the Public Prosecutor’s Agent attached to the Court, Ramiro Arias, questioned García Gómez if the damage had been repaired and who of the partners of the bookmaker was the one who granted the pardon, although the lawyer tried to reserve the name.
On the basis of file 197/2011 the legal pardon is granted to Jonás Larrazábal and henceforth no claim can be filed around the process that was followed; in addition to that he will not be required reparation for damages or punishment.
After the hearing with the legal representative of the bookmaker, at about 15:50 Larrazabal Bretón was immediately released.
The secretary of the court, Jorge Yánez, moved to the prison of the municipality of San Nicolás de los Garza to notify Jonás that he has been legally pardoned and his file will be archived.
It will also notify you of the immediate release order issued by the judge.
Secretary Dionisio Perez Jácome gives details of the plane crash where the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake, and seven other people lost their lives
The Secretary of Communications and Transportation (SCT) reported that the results released on the accident where the Secretary of the Interior, Francisco Blake Mora, and seven other people lost their lives, indicate that the helicopter was hit directly on the ground in complete structural integrity, without the pilot could attempt a forced landing.
During a press conference, Dionisio Pérez Jácome, Secretary of Communications and Transportation, mentioned that before taking off the aircraft, the pilot found that the weather conditions were suitable for flying.
"The elements that seem to indicate that the unit had several contacts with the ground, the blades had contact with trees 25 meters away where the unit lost the fuselage."
It also reported that the unit was designed for 19 people, so it had the necessary requirements to transport the personnel.
In addition, he said that the investigations made in the area of the impact are not reported the appearance of pieces on the ground.
"In a search that there are no parts or components of the spacecraft elsewhere, the impact was presented structurally.
"The design of the helicopter was for 19 passengers, it had adequate requirements to transport passengers.
The terrain presents a slope of seven degrees at 30 degrees of inclination.
At the moment, the secretary said it is a priority to have the results as soon as possible; however, the investigation can last several months, even could reach a year.
Gilberto López Meyer, Director General of Airports and Auxiliary Services, said that at the time of the impact, the Presidential General Staff helicopter was operating at cruise speed and that this happened in soft uphill terrain.
"This information strengthens the hypothesis of a normal cruise operation at the time of impact," he said.
At the press conference, the head of the SCT, Pérez Jácome, listed six relevant elements in the research:
Visual flight:
In accordance with aeronautical regulations the flight was carried out under visual flight rules, this implies that the crew must have visibility during the flight and on the ground.
Meteorological conditions:
The reports in the AICM located suitable conditions for take-off, as the aircraft advances towards the border area between the DF and the State of Mexico there were cloud layers at low altitude.
Selected routes:
It is likely that due to the cloudy conditions the crew has sought an area of lower elevation and greater visibility towards the valley of Cuernavaca.
Location of the impact.
The impact coordinates and the last radar aircraft record coincide, probably before the impact there was no loss of control or alteration in the flight path.
Dispersion of aircraft debris in a small area:
The information available so far makes it possible to assume that the impact occurred in a straight and sideways trajectory.
The debris scattering pattern of the aircraft allows to assume that the helicopter was impacted on the ground in conditions of structural integrity.
No evidence of fire or explosion has been detected:
At the site of the accident there is still no evidence of any kind of explosion or fire in the wreckage of the ship.
The latest results of the investigation indicate that he may have had multiple contacts with the ground.
During the fieldwork, parts of the aircraft have been found at an elevation of 9,200 feet above average sea level, the terrain presents a slope ranging from seven degrees to 30 degrees of inclination.
The photographs show the sequence in which it predictably disjointed along that path.
The information provides elements that seem to indicate that the helicopter may have had multiple impacts on the ground.
After a thorough search in a wider area than the cordoned off site around the crash, no scattered parts of the aircraft have been found, strengthening the presumption that the impact occurred under structural integrity conditions.
MSS Announces Protocol to Find Obesity Gene
Social Security Leads Research to Discover Obesity Gene in Children and Young People; Supported by IPN Specialists
The Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) has announced that it is conducting research to discover the obesity gene in children and young people, called the protocol 'Genetics of childhood and adolescence obesity', which will allow to have markers associated with overweight.
In a statement, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital de Especialidades of the National Medical Center Siglo XXI, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was integrated.
This team is supported by specialists and postgraduate students of the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Center for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation, the population is invited to participate, whether or not they have the right, to go to the participating sports units of the IMSS in the Valley of Mexico, where tests are carried out on minors, every Saturday from 8:00 am.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Cuauhtémoc Sports Unit (Mexico State West) and that since October 8, the activity is carried out in the Nezahualcóyolt Sports Unit (Mexico State East).
Once the goal of bringing together 500 or 600 minors is met, the study will continue in the Unidad Deportiva Independencia (south of the Federal District) and finally in the Unidad Deportiva Morelos (north of the Federal District).
He explained that the purpose of this research is to know the components and the importance of genetics with respect to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors in Mexican children and young people to prevent the appearance of chronic degenerative diseases.
Celebrating World Diabetes Day on November 14, he said the goal is to bring together 3,000 children and young people between the ages of six and 14, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific questionnaires on diet.
They will also be asked about physical activity and hereditary family history of disease, in order to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
He detailed that on Saturdays anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference), blood pressure measurements, determination of glucose, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin levels and genetics (they seek to identify genes associated with childhood obesity) are applied to all participants.
Cruz López pointed out that this research is due to the concern of health professionals about the alarming weight gain in minors.
"The health surveys of 1999 and 2006 indicated that in just six years there was an increase, in the case of boys, of 77 percent in obesity, and of girls of 47 percent; in terms of overweight, there was also a dramatic increase," said the IMSS specialist.
He indicated that the justification for the search for the markers is based on the fact that the population of the country differs from others by its genetic history.
He reported that on average, the Mexican has 65 percent American Indian, 30 percent European and five percent African heritage and this condition is reflected in genes that are associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translates into the inability to burn excess energy that we consume (calories) and that is stored in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit for the participants is the comprehensive evaluation of the children, which allows detecting if they are overweight or obese.
Even, he said, the presence of dark-colored folds (acantosis) on the neck and forearm, indicating the likelihood of metabolic alterations and even prediabetes.
The information is handled confidentially, doctors deliver it in writing to parents, who are explained each of the measurements and lifestyle changes they must make to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentary lifestyle, which is the lack of daily physical activity, sitting most of the day in front of the television and using means of transport instead of walking short distances.
